Overview

In this lab, we introduce ggplot package for data visualization. This package is one of the packages in tidyverse. You do not need to install ggplot if you have installed tidyverse.

The package ggplot is a very powerful visualization tool, which is flexible enough to produce all kinds of plots. We will focus on some basic plots:

  • Histogram: shows distribution of a numeric variable;
  • Scatter plot: shows relationship between two numeric variables;
  • Bar plot: shows distribution of a categorical variable.
library(tidyverse)

As always, we need to set the correct working directory, the folder where your data are located. Below is the path of my working directory. You should modify it accordingly. Then we load the data. We will use the movie data for this lab.

# set working directory (modify the path accordingly)
setwd("C:/Users/Shaobo Li/Dropbox/Teaching/KU/data")
# load data
movie<- read_csv("movie.csv")

R basic plot

We may start from R basic plot, which is less flexible comparing to ggplot.

histogram for individual variables

hist(movie$imdb_score, col = "blue")

We can use the option below to set the window to display two figures (arranged in 1 row 2 columns).

# set display arrangement
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
# now we can draw two graphs in one window
hist(movie$imdb_score, col = "blue")
hist(log(movie$budget), col = "blue")

This only applies for R basic plot

scatter plot of two variables

plot(movie$budget, movie$gross)

plot(log(movie$budget), log(movie$gross))

boxplot

boxplot(log(movie$gross)~movie$content_rating, col=rainbow(5))

ggplot

ggplot has its own syntax. It draws figure based on multiple layers.

Histogram

ggplot(data=movie)+
  geom_histogram(mapping=aes(x=imdb_score), fill="blue")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

The first function ggplot(data=movie) creates an empty plot, which is the first layer of you graph, just like you grab a white plain paper. Then, add another layer uning the function geom_histogram(). It stands for â€œgeometric object - histogramâ€. Of course there are different types of geometric object, such as points, curves, straight lines, boxes, etc. You will see!

Each geom function in ggplot2 takes a mapping argument. This defines how variables in your dataset are mapped to visual properties. aes stands for aesthetic, which specifies what data you want to map (draw). Therefore, the mapping argument is always paired with aes().

Here is a template to produce graphs using ggplot2

ggplot(data = <DATA>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))

You can have many graphic options in the . For example, you can add the boundary color and specify the number of bins.

ggplot(movie)+
  geom_histogram(aes(x=imdb_score), fill="blue", color="black", bins=20)

You can also place the aes() inside ggplot().

ggplot(movie, aes(x=imdb_score))+
  geom_histogram(fill="blue", color="black", bins=20)

The y-axis of above histograms is frequency, but we can change it to density (proportion). And we can also add an estimated density curve on top of it.

ggplot(movie, aes(x=imdb_score, y=..density..))+
  geom_histogram(fill="blue", color="black", bins=20)+
  geom_density(color="red")

In above code, y=..density.. changes the y-axis to the density scale, geom_density() is to add another layer, which is an estimated density curve.

Histogram by group

We can compare the distribution of a variable across different groups by drawing an overlaid histogram or completely separate them. For example, how do we compare the distribution of log(budget) across different content rating (e.g., PG, PG-13 and R)?

## first let's subset the data by filtering content rating with only PG, PG-13, and R
movie1 <- filter(movie, content_rating%in%c("PG", "PG-13", "R"))
ggplot(movie1, aes(x=log(budget), y=..density..))+
  geom_histogram(position = "identity", alpha=0.4, aes(fill=content_rating))+  
  geom_density(aes(color=content_rating))+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("PG"="green", "PG-13"="blue", "R"="red"))+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("PG"="green", "PG-13"="blue", "R"="red"))

In above code, position = "identity" specifies overlaid histogram of each group (what if we do not specify it?), alpha is the level of transparency of the color filling, scale_fill_manual() is to manually specify the filling color for each group, so does scale_color_manual().

Exercise:

Remove the density curve change the scale of y-axis to frequency. What do you see? Why?

From this overlaid histogram, we can tell some differences, but most part are overlapped. This makes the figure itself not appealing. So we can separate them to three different histograms but align them with the same x-axis.

ggplot(movie1, aes(x=log(budget), y=..density..))+
  geom_histogram(position = "identity", alpha=0.4, aes(fill=content_rating))+  # alpha is the level of transparency
  geom_density(aes(color=content_rating))+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("PG"="green", "PG-13"="blue", "R"="red"))+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("PG"="green", "PG-13"="blue", "R"="red"))+
  facet_wrap(~content_rating, nrow = 3)

In above code, facet_wrap() splits the figure by group.

Boxplot

Boxplot is useful when you want to learn the location of a continuous variable. Here is a good tutorial to understand boxplot link.

Following previous example, we can use boxplot to answer the same question.

ggplot(movie1, aes(x=content_rating, y=log(budget)))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(color=content_rating))+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("PG"="green", "PG-13"="blue", "R"="red"))

Scatter plot

ggplot(data=movie, aes(x=log(budget), y=log(gross)))+
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 1152 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

You can change the color, shape, and size of the dots.

ggplot(movie, aes(log(budget), log(gross)))+
  geom_point(color="red", shape=5, size=2)
## Warning: Removed 1152 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

The figure below tells you which number stands for which shape.

Add a fitted line or curve

ggplot(movie, aes(log(budget), log(gross)))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()  
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

This adds a fitted smooth curve. You can also change it to a linear line.

ggplot(movie, aes(log(budget), log(gross)))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Show different groups

Again, letâ€™s simply consider movies whose content ratings are â€œPGâ€, â€œPG-13â€ and â€œRâ€.

ggplot(movie1, aes(log(budget), log(gross), color=content_rating))+
  geom_point(size=2)

The content_rating is the third dimension in this figure. That is why it has to be in aes().

Split to multiple figures by group

ggplot(movie1, aes(log(budget), log(gross), color=content_rating))+
  geom_point(size=2)+
  facet_wrap(~content_rating, nrow=3)

Correlation plot

Correlation plot is a useful tool to visualization pairwise correlation between multiple numeric variables. It is essentially a heatmap where the color scale represents the strength of correlation.

For example, we want examine the correlation between â€œIMDB scoreâ€, â€œdurationâ€, â€œlog(budget)â€ and â€œlog(gross)â€.

# first, select these four columns (we will learn these functions in next lab)
movie1 <- movie%>%
  mutate(log_budget=log(budget), log_gross=log(gross))%>%
  select(imdb_score, duration, log_budget, log_gross)%>%
  na.omit()
# second, calculate correlation
cormat <- cor(movie1)
# finally, create correlation plot
library(corrplot)
corrplot(cormat)

Bar plot

Bar plot is like histogram, but it is for categorical variable. It is also very useful when compare certain statistic across different groups.

Univariate bar plot

ggplot(movie, aes(x=content_rating))+
  geom_bar()

We see the x label is not well displayed. We can make it vertical.

ggplot(movie, aes(x=content_rating))+
  geom_bar()+
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1,vjust=0.5))

Or we can flip the a-axis and y-axis.

ggplot(movie, aes(x=content_rating))+
  geom_bar()+
  coord_flip()

It might be more useful to show the proportion rather than count on y-axis.

ggplot(movie, aes(x=content_rating))+
  geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)))+
  ylab("Proportion")+
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1,vjust=0.5))

Exercise

Can you fill different color for those bars in above figure?

Bar plot for multiple variables

Let us first create a new variable, which is categorized imdb score. Then we filter the 4 most popular content ratings.

# categorization
cate_score<- cut(movie$imdb_score, breaks=c(0, 4, 6, 7, 10), labels=c("poor", "okay", "good", "great"))
movie$cate_score<- cate_score
# filtering
index<- movie$content_rating %in% c("R", "PG", "PG-13", "G")
movie1<- movie[index,]

Categorical vs.Â categorical

Now both cate_score and content_rating are categorical variables. Is there a way to show whether these two variables are dependent?

We can use different color for second categorical variable to be displayed on each bar.

ggplot(movie1, aes(x=cate_score, fill=content_rating))+
  geom_bar()

Can this plot help you answering the question? Probably not, because the count varies across cate_score. We can modify it such that the height of the bar are all the same while we show the proportion of different content_raing.

ggplot(movie1, aes(x=cate_score, fill=content_rating))+
  geom_bar(position = "fill")

Now what do you think? Is this figure helpful? What is your conclusion to previous question? You can also put the actual proportion values on the figure. Can you do Google search to figure it out?

Categorical vs.Â continuous

Do you think higher scored movies have higher gross? You may draw scatter plot to answer this question. But if one of the variables is categorical, such as the categorized imdb score, bar plot is a better choice.

However, you need first get the average gross for each category. It is essentially calculating some summary statistcs. Therefore, we use function stat_summary() instead of directly using geom_bar(). You can specify different geom in stat_summary().

ggplot(movie1, aes(x=cate_score, y=gross))+
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom="bar", fill="blue", na.rm = T)+
  ylab("Avg. gross")
## Warning: The `fun.y` argument of `stat_summary()` is deprecated as of ggplot2 3.3.0.
## â„¹ Please use the `fun` argument instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.

Now what if you also want to look at different content ratings?

ggplot(movie1, aes(x=cate_score, y=gross, fill= content_rating))+
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom="bar", na.rm = T, position = "dodge")+
  ylab("Avg. gross")

Movie genres and bar plot

In this section we show how to handle variables like genres. Each movie has multiple genres, and they are separated by â€œ|â€. We know how to separate them into different columns in Excel. We now show how to work it out in R. We need another package tm, which was built for text mining.

Create sparse matrix for genre

library(tm)
genres<- (sapply(movie$genres,gsub,pattern="\\|",replacement=" "))
genre.sparse.mat <- DocumentTermMatrix(Corpus(VectorSource(genres)))
genre.sparse.mat<- as.matrix(genre.sparse.mat)

Average score for each genre

mat.score<- genre.sparse.mat*movie$imdb_score
apply(ifelse(mat.score==0, NA, mat.score), 2, median, na.rm=TRUE)
##      action   adventure     fantasy      sci-fi    thriller documentary 
##        6.30        6.60        6.40        6.40        6.40        7.40 
##     romance   animation      comedy      family     musical     mystery 
##        6.50        6.70        6.30        6.40        6.70        6.60 
##     western       drama     history       sport       crime      horror 
##        6.80        6.90        7.20        6.80        6.60        5.90 
##         war   biography       music   game-show  reality-tv        news 
##        7.10        7.20        6.60        2.90        4.75        7.40 
##       short   film-noir 
##        6.50        7.65

Bar plot

How to draw a bar plot for the numbers we got above? A more general question is: how to draw a bar plot given the summary statistics?

You will need to create new data frame with one column being the genre name and the other being the average scores.

genre_score<- data.frame(genre=colnames(mat.score), 
                         avg_imdb_score=apply(ifelse(mat.score==0, NA, mat.score), 2, median, na.rm=TRUE))

Then draw the bar chart.

ggplot(genre_score, aes(x=genre, y=avg_imdb_score))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1,vjust=0.5))

stat="identity" means it directly plot the values of y as the height of y-axis.

Exercise

Can you get the frequency (count) instead of average score as the y-axis?
